It&#39;s only a few months before  PHP 8 will be released, and honestly there are so many good features. In this post I want to share the real-life impact that PHP 8 will have on my own code.
   I&#39;m going to try not to abuse  attributes, but I think configuring event listeners is an example of an annotation I&#39;ll be using extensively.
 You might know that I&#39;ve been working on  event sourced systems lately, and I can tell you: there&#39;s lots of event configuration to do. Take this simple projector, for example:
 // Before  class    implements  {  use  ;  protected  array $handlesEvents = [  CartStartedEvent::class =&gt;  &#39;onCartStarted&#39;,  CartItemAddedEvent::class =&gt;  &#39;onCartItemAdded&#39;,  CartItemRemovedEvent::class =&gt;  &#39;onCartItemRemoved&#39;,  CartExpiredEvent::class =&gt;  &#39;onCartExpired&#39;,  CartCheckedOutEvent::class =&gt;  &#39;onCartCheckedOut&#39;,  CouponAddedToCartItemEvent::class =&gt;  &#39;onCouponAddedToCartItem&#39;, ];  public   function   ( CartStartedEvent $event):   {  /* … */ }  public   function   ( CartItemAddedEvent $event):   {  /* … */ }  public   function   ( CartItemRemovedEvent $event):   {  /* … */ }  public   function   ( CartCheckedOutEvent $event):   {  /* … */ }  public   function   ( CartExpiredEvent $event):   {  /* … */ }  public   function   ( CouponAddedToCartItemEvent $event):   {  /* … */ }}
   Event listener configuration and handlers are put together, I don&#39;t have to scroll to the top of the file to know whether a listener is configured correctly.
 I don&#39;t have to bother anymore writing and managing method names as strings: your IDE can&#39;t autocomplete them, there&#39;s no static analysis on typos and method renaming doesn&#39;t work.
  class    implements  {  use  ;  #[ SubscribesTo( CartStartedEvent ::class)]  public   function   ( CartStartedEvent $event):   {  /* … */ }  #[ SubscribesTo( CartItemAddedEvent ::class)]  public   function   ( CartItemAddedEvent $event):   {  /* … */ }  #[ SubscribesTo( CartItemRemovedEvent ::class)]  public   function   ( CartItemRemovedEvent $event):   {  /* … */ }  #[ SubscribesTo( CartCheckedOutEvent ::class)]  public   function   ( CartCheckedOutEvent $event):   {  /* … */ }  #[ SubscribesTo( CartExpiredEvent ::class)]  public   function   ( CartExpiredEvent $event):   {  /* … */ }  #[ SubscribesTo( CouponAddedToCartItemEvent ::class)]  public   function   ( CouponAddedToCartItemEvent $event):   {  /* … */ }}
   A smaller one, but this one will have a day-by-day impact. I often find myself still needing doc blocks because of two things: static return types and generics. The latter one can&#39;t be solved yet, but luckily the first one will in PHP 8!
       I&#39;m writing a new book called  Front Line PHP. It&#39;s about PHP 8 and modern PHP development in general. I plan to release it in December, you can already  subscribe to the mailing list to stay up to date!
  If you read my blog, you know I wrote quite a bit about the use of PHP&#39;s type system combined with  data transfer objects. Naturally, I use lots of DTOs in my own code, so you can imagine how happy I am, being able to rewrite this:
 class    extends  {  public  string  $name;  public  string  $email;  public  int  $age;  public  static   function   (  CustomerRequest $request ):   {  return  new  self([  &#39;name&#39; =&gt; $request-&gt; get( &#39;name&#39;),  &#39;email&#39; =&gt; $request-&gt; get( &#39;email&#39;),  &#39;age&#39; =&gt; $request-&gt; get( &#39;age&#39;), ]); }}$data =  CustomerData:: fromRequest($customerRequest);
   class  {  public   function   (  public  string  $name,  public  string  $email,  public  int  $age, ) {}}$data =  new  CustomerData(...$customerRequest-&gt; validated());
  Note the use of both  constructor property promotion, as well as named arguments. Yes, they can be passed using named arrays and the spread operator!
  Do you sometimes find yourself using an enum with some methods on it, that will give a different result based on the enum value?
 /** *   static self PENDING() *   static self PAID() */  class    extends  {  private  const PENDING =  &#39;pending&#39;;  private  const PAID =  &#39;paid&#39;;  public   function   ():   {  return [  self::PENDING =&gt;  &#39;orange&#39;,  self::PAID =&gt;  &#39;green&#39;, ][ $this-&gt; value] ??  &#39;gray&#39;; }}
  I would argue that for more complex conditions, you&#39;re better off using  the state pattern, yet there are cases where an enum does suffice. This weird array syntax already is a shorthand for a more verbose conditional:
 /** *   static self PENDING() *   static self PAID() */  class    extends  {  private  const PENDING =  &#39;pending&#39;;  private  const PAID =  &#39;paid&#39;;  public   function   ():   {  if ( $this-&gt; value ===  self::PENDING) {  return  &#39;orange&#39;; }  if ( $this-&gt; value ===  self::PAID) {  return  &#39;green&#39; }  return  &#39;gray&#39;; }}
   /** *   static self PENDING() *   static self PAID() */  class    extends  {  private  const PENDING =  &#39;pending&#39;;  private  const PAID =  &#39;paid&#39;;  public   function   ():   {  return  match ( $this-&gt;value) {  self::PENDING =&gt;  &#39;orange&#39;,  self::PAID =&gt;  &#39;green&#39;,   default =&gt;  &#39;gray&#39;, }; }}
   When I mentioned the   static return type before, I forgot another use case where docblock type hints were required: union types. At least, they were required before, because PHP 8 supports them natively!
